a onetime chief aide to former hud secretary 
samuel pierce refused wednesday to answer questions from a house 
subcommittee investigating the agency saying he had been labeled a 
prime candidate for a criminal investigation 
lance h wilson asserted his fifth amendment right against 
selfincrimination just as pierce did a day earlier 
during the days proceedings a former hud staffer told of 
investigating a project on behalf of a contributor to president 
bushs 1980 campaign for the vice presidency 
my counsel has advised me that it is unwise for anyone labeled 
a prime candidate for a criminal investigation to testify under 
such circumstances wilson told the employment and housing 
subcommittee of the house committee on government operations 
echoing comments pierce made tuesday wilson said he was 
convinced the subcommittee had already prejudged me 
pressed by committee members on how he had been prejudged 
wilson cited a comment by rep christopher shays rconn at a 
july hearing at which wilson failed to appear 
shays said then he was convinced people would be prosecuted for 
influencepeddling and fraud at hud and that wilson was a prime 
candidate for criminal investigation 
wilson is the fourth former department of housing and urban 
development official to cite the fifth amendment 
deborah gore dean who in 1984 succeeded wilson as pierces 
chief aide and r hunter cushing former director of huds 
multifamily housing programs asserted the same rights in hearings 
during the summer 
however only pierce and wilson alleged they had been prejudged 
former regional hud officials in testimony wednesday described 
wilson as the man to see for getting approval of hud grant loan or 
guarantee applications both during and after his tenure at the 
agency 
dick eudaley who headed huds fivestate regional office in 
fort worth texas from 1982 to may 1984 said wilson had told him 
that a 7 million apartment project in fort worth was going to be 
approved despite unanimous opposition from the agencys technical 
staff 
the feeling within the agency was that this project had the 
personal interest of the secretarys office and mr wilson 
eudaley said 
the 800unit regalridge apartment project developed by fort 
worth real estate developer leonard briscoe is now in shambles 
financially eudaley said 
two years later briscoe gave wilson a 15 percent interest in 
the 24 million wedgewood plaza apartment project briscoe was 
developing in riviera beach fla lantos said 
alexander naclerio former director of housing in huds new york 
area office said he was called at home by wilson on a weekend 
evening in 1982 and asked to look into a project in puerto rico 
wilson indicated this was on behalf of a major contributor to 
george bushs vice presidential campaign delio rojo naclerio 
testified 
naclerio said he reported his findings to wilson that revenue 
from nearby commercial property owned by rojo be used to reduce the 
required subsidies 
the washington post said in thursday editions that hud officials 
it did not identify had reported an aide to bush asked wilson to 
meet with rojo about the project 
the newspaper said aides to vice president bush said they made 
referrals to government agencies without endorsements 
rojos consultant carlos figueroa said he arranged the 
rojowilson meeting on his own and probably discussed the matter 
with rafael v capo an aide to the vice president 
naclerio who became a consultant after retiring in 1986 said 
he sent wilson a 5000 check that year after getting a 15000 
check from a puerto rican developer who had sought help on a hud 
rehabilitation project 
naclerio said he also sent a 10000 check to wilson in seeking 
hud mortgage assistance for a 123 million 467unit apartment 
project in manhattan after being told that the departments 
approval was being held up because i had a problem with hunter 
cushing 
naclerio a 39year career employee at hud before his 
retirement said wilson called back and said cushing assured him 
there would be no interference 
wilson a vice president of paine webber group inc an 
investment banking house took the fifth amendment four times to 
questions posed by subcommittees chairman rep tom lantos 
dcalif 
after several bitter exchanges between his lawyer and lantos he 
did answer two questions posed by shays 
shays asked if huds inspector general who earlier this year 
released a report finding widespread problems in the departments 
moderate rehabilitation housing subsidy program had tried to 
interview him and if he had in fact been interviewed 
wilson responded yes to having been asked to meet with the 
inspector general and no to whether they met asked to explain 
why he didnt meet with the inspector general wilson again cited 
the fifth amendment 
you have a lot of similarity with your boss samuel pierce 
because he basically did the same thing shays said he used 
every excuse not to meet with the ig inspector general like you 
did 
wilsons lawyer raymond banoun tried to object but was 
lectured by lantos you will not interrupt a member of this 
committee 
outside the hearing room banoun assailed the committee members 
for ridiculing someone because he asserted his constitutional 
rights 
wilson requested and was granted a leave from paine webber after 
his name surfaced in lantos investigation 
paine webber chairman donald b marron told the subcommittee 
wednesday that wilson had not sought approval to engage in outside 
business activities such as consulting as required by the 
companys code of conduct 
wilson signed a statement at the end of 1988 certifying that he 
had abided by the company code marron said 
james treadway a paine webber vice president who conducted an 
internal inquiry into wilsons activities after charges surfaced 
that he used political connections to attract hudrelated business 
for the company said the probe turned up nothing improper 
lantos cited paine webber documents indicating that wilson had 
spent more than 10000 entertaining hud officials 
to the extent they the expenses are personal we will seek 
reimbursement he said 
