<TEXT>
senate majority leader george mitchell accused 
president bush today of being overly timid and urged him to 
suspend trade restrictions with the soviet union as a reward for 
permitting freer emigration 
mitchell called for the temporary waiver of the jacksonvanik 
amendment which links nondiscriminatory trade treatment by the 
united states with the freedom of soviet citizens to leave their 
country at will 
the democratic leader noted that more than 100000 people have 
been permitted to leave the soviet union since the beginning of the 
year and that as many as 50000 more have received permission to 
depart 
this indisputable rise in soviet emiagration is a step that 
deserves an american response mitchell told the senate the 
response quite clearly should be the conditional lifting of 
impediments to trade imposed by the jacksonvanik amendment 
the jacksonvanik amendment was adopted by congress in 1974 at 
the height of the cold war named for its principal sponsors the 
late sen henry m jackson dwash and former rep charles a 
vanik dohio the amendment bars the extension of trade credits 
and the granting of mostfavored nation trade status to communist 
nations which deny citizens the freedom to emigrate 
mitchell noted that the law permits the president to waive the 
amendment if he determines soviet citizens are no longer denied the 
right to leave or if such a waiver will promote freedom of 
emigration 
he said lifting the amendment would not automatically confer 
dramatic trade benefits that a ussoviet commercial agreement 
would be needed to do that and that trade would continue to be 
limited by a lack of demand for soviet products 
but jacksonvanik is of tremendous symbolic importance 
mitchell said noting that soviet leaders have long cited it as an 
obstacle to closer relations 
bush has said he will consider waiving the amendment only when 
the soviets formally change their emigration laws and when the 
results of that change are seen to be both visible and permament 
i believe this is an overly timid approach mitchell said 
declaring that soviet emigration levels are now three times what 
they were in 1979 the previous highwater mark 
if the president temporarily waives jacksonvanik he loses 
nothing he can only win mitchell said 
he can refuse to renew it should the soviets restrict 
emigration or refuse to codify their emigration laws and i would 
be among the first to urge him to do so the majority leader said 
waiving the law now would conform with the intent of the 
amendment provide a carrot and stick to influence the future 
of soviet emigration and demonstrate that ussoviet trade is 
primarily limited by the failure of the soviet economic system not 
by us actions he said 
it is disappointing that the president has failed to recognize 
that the goals of jacksonvanik have been met mitchell said 
president bush should accept victory and respond accordingly 
</TEXT>
