a transplant drug that suppresses the immune 
system appears to relieve severe crohns disease a lingering 
inflammation of the digestive tract according to a report 
danish doctors found that the medicine called cyclosporine 
seemed to help some people who did not respond to standard 
treatment with steroid drugs 
cyclosporine is ordinarily used to stop the bodys rejection of 
transplanted organs while useful the drug can damage the kidneys 
the disease which affects the intestines causes recurring 
attacks of cramps and diarrhea symptoms are relatively mild in 
about threequarters of victims 
the latest study was conducted by dr jorn brynskov and 
colleagues at herlov university hospital in copenhagen it was 
published in thursdays new england journal of medicine 
during three months of treatment 22 of 37 patients given 
cyclosporine showed improvement compared with 11 of 34 of those 
who took placebos during a threemonth followup the improvement 
continued to 38 percent of the cyclosporine patients and 15 percent 
in the comparison group 
the researchers said their results were rather encouraging 
but they said more study is needed and this treatment should be 
limited for now to formal research experiments 
in an accompanying editorial dr david b sachar of mt sinai 
school of medicine in new york said the research establishes a 
new treatment for crohns disease that works 
he said the best use of the drug may be to induce a quick 
fix in serously ill patients who fail to respond to steroids 
this could buy time for sloweracting longterm medicines to take 
effect 
