<TEXT>
a lebanese man serving a life sentence for the 
attempted assassination of a former iranian prime minister said 
wednesday he would pay damages to the victims of his attack in 
exchange for his release from prison 
in a statement issued by his lawyers anis naccache said his 
proposal would improve franceiranian relations there was no 
immediate response from the french government to the proposal 
the lawyers jacques verges and antoine comte also told 
reporters that their client had nothing to do with last weeks 
crash of a french airliner en route from ndjamena chad to paris 
there has been speculation that the uta flight on which 171 
people died could have been bombed in an effort to press for 
naccaches release 
iranian officials have called publicly for naccache to be freed 
but france has denied widespread reports that it agreed last year 
to free him as part of a deal for the release of the remaining us 
hostages in iran 
naccache led a fiveman team that tried to kill shahpour 
bakhtiar the last iranian premier before the islamic revolution 
outside his paris exile home in 1980 bakhtiar was unhurt but a 
neighbor and a policeman were killed and three other people injured 
at his trial naccache said he was carrying out orders from 
irans islamic authorities 
naccaches statement also urged the release of the four others 
convicted in the attack 
comte said the precise amount naccache would pay those injured 
in the attack and relatives of those killed had not been set but 
would amount to several million francs one million francs is 
equivalent to about 160000 
asked where naccache could get the money comte said one can 
deduce that iran would help pay for his release 
