<DOCNO> AP890927-0144 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
although more physicians are being disciplined 
by state regulators lax treatment of negligence still poses a 
serious risk to public health a health research group said 
wednesday 
state licensing boards took serious disciplinary actions 
license revocation suspension or probation against 1495 
physicians in 1987 a 17 percent increase over the previous year 
said a public citizen health research group report 
nationally thats a rate of nearly three serious actions for 
every 1000 doctors 
but some states continue to be more vigilant than others in 
weeding out bad doctors and in some states physicians can still 
operate drunk commit a gross act of negligence or sexually 
assault a patient and receive a mere slap on the wrist the 
report said 
the numbers are based on actions reported by the federation of 
state medical boards whose executive vice president bryant 
galusha agreed that the number of actions has been increasing but 
said the public citizen report does not present a full picture 
galusha said the group failed to tally the 1106 remedial 
actions state boards took in 1987 by which physicians are allowed 
to continue practicing with certain limitations also not all 
actions taken are disciplinary in nature such as when a board 
denies a license he said 
these protect the public too galusha said 
public citizen estimates that more than 100000 americans are 
injured or killed each year because of physicians negligence and 
that lax treatment of physicians negligence is one of the most 
serious threats to the health of american patients 
the public interest group associated with ralph nader said 
serious disciplinary actions against physicians have more than 
doubled since 1984 and attributes the rise to a spate of adverse 
publicity and state and federal legislation 
during 1987 and 1988 44 state legislatures strengthened state 
oversight of physicians the group said 
also the federations physician disciplinary data bank a 
computerized network linking all the state boards has made it 
easier for states to keep track of errant doctors galusha said 
were hardly ever seeing a physician once theres an action 
taken against him pack his bag and go to another state without 
being detected its very difficult for that to happen now whereas 
five years ago it was done with relative ease galusha said 
the most common charge against doctors leading to a serious 
disciplinary action is incompetence said sidney wolfe a physician 
and head of the health research group other charges include 
writing an excessive number of prescriptions for controlled 
substances and personally abusing drugs he said 
the group recommends raising doctors licensing fees to 500 per 
year to finance doctor disciplinary actions and reduce the backlogs 
that plague many state medical boards 
public citizen also recommends periodic recertification of 
physicians giving state boards broader authority to evaluate 
doctors and take action against them and requiring insurance 
companies to rate doctors so those with the best records pay the 
lowest premiums 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

