americans will drive 4 trillion miles in 2007 
about double the number they drove in 1987 a transportation trade 
group executive said wednesday 
a growing desire for mobility will account for most of the 
growth in traffic said francis b francois executive director of 
the american association of street highway and transportation 
officials 
americans drove 2 trillion miles in 1987 about triple what 
they drove in 1956 francois said this is not the 1950s where 
american families had one car which dad may or may not have driven 
to work because he took public transportation 
both government and commuters must accept new ways to pay for 
new roads and improvements to existing ones said francois and 
others at a news conference where they presented findings of a 
congestion study sponsored by the urban land institute 
the institute is a research group supported in part by real 
estate developers 
there is the prevailing sentiment in local government to 
approach the problem simplistically like if you stop development 
you will stop traffic growth that is clearly not the case 
northern virginia developer and study director james defrancia said 
even with no new real estate development in the suburbs traffic 
would increase the study argued 
in norrs has increased twice as fast as population defrancia said 
nationally the number of miles driven and the number of cars 
increased about 55 percent from 1969 to 1983 and the number of 
drivers rose 43 percent while the population increased only 14 
percent 
the institute recommended greater use of public transit and car 
pools as well as new financing to reduce road congestion 
the united states spent about 66 billion on its roads in 1987 
but should be spending at least 80 billion annually just to 
maintain old roads and build the most vital new ones francois said 
it should be 100 billion to really meet all the needs he 
said 
