voters passed a referendum mandating reduced rates helped prompt 
the industry to join the coalition the referendum was promoted by 
consumer advocate ralph nader 
theres no doubt the california referendum has heightened in 
the minds of our industry the fact that the public is now expecting 
an increased amount of effort in participation on problems 
maatman said 
in a telephone interview nader said the insurance industry had 
taken a first step toward fulfilling its neglected responsibility 
in loss prevention 
nader said that without the california referendum insurance 
companies never would have done this 
insurance companies and groups representing 40 percent of the 
american automobile insurance market have pledged 15 million for 
the organizations efforts in the first year stone said 
at the federal leval the group backs a senate bill to extend 
current auto safety features to trucks and vans it also adds 
features to protect against impact from side collisions and require 
motorcycle helmet usage antilock brakes and passenger side air 
bags 
the group also wants a return to the 55 mph speed limit on all 
interstate highways in 1987 congress allowed states to raise the 
speed limit to 65 mph on rural stretches of interstates 
at the state and local level the group plans to push issues 
such as drunken driving safety belts and child seats 
insurance discounts for using safety devices are not among the 
groups priorities 
we will work hard to make this marriage work and well worry 
about whether we have any children later maatman said of 
divisive issues that might come up later 
consumer advocate groups that will be part of the coalition 
include public citizen a naderfounded group in addition safety 
and medical experts will also be on the group 
