<TEXT>
radio free europe and radio liberty 
opened a bureau in budapest on wednesday the first in eastern 
europe for the two usfunded radio stations 
the opening of this bureau is less a cause for surprise than a 
reflection of the fact that hungary is open to the free flow of 
ideas the stations president eugene pel said at the official 
opening 
hungary became the first soviet bloc country to accredit a 
permanent correspondent from the stations in may 
us ambassador mark palmer said rfe is a strange institution 
because its very aim is to selfdestruct we hope it will 
achieve this in hungary 
radio free europe was founded in 1949 and radio liberty two 
years later to inform people in the soviet union and eastern europe 
about issues they could not learn from the official media 
however in the wake of farreaching political reforms 
hungarian state media have become increasingly open and critical 
the sister stations with headquarters in munich west germany 
are controlled by the washingtonbased board of international 
broadcasting and are funded by the us government 
radio liberty broadcasts in 12 languages to the soviet union 
while radio free europe transmits to bulgaria czechoslovakia 
hungary poland and romania as well as the soviet states of 
lithuania latvia and estonia they reach about 55 million people 
after being jammed for decades the stations recently have 
benefited from a spirit of openness being promoted by soviet 
president mikhail s gorbachev 
however palmer noted some warsaw pact members still are 
resistant to reform there are still some countries in the region 
which need radio free europe he said 
the budapest office is to be staffed by a correspondent from the 
stations news and current affairs division and by programmers from 
hungarys broadcasting department it is to broadcast daily news 
and reports about hungarian events and issues as well as live 
programs station officials said 
wednesdays reception was attended by leading members of all the 
main opposition parties and groups in hungary 
none of the invited communist leaders were there but us 
officials familiar with hungarian affairs suggested they may have 
stayed away because of political commitments 
parliament is meeting this week to discuss key legislation to 
pave the way for transition to a multiparty system the communist 
party also is to hold a key congress in budapest next week at which 
reformists and hardliners are expected to clash 
in the past the communist leadership perceived radio free 
europe as a subversive force 
during the anticommunist uprising in 1956 radio free europe 
broadcasts led many hungarians to believe the west would help when 
soviet troops invaded to crush the revolt this did not 
materialize and many hungarians have remained resentful 
nevertheless the station is popular in hungary particularly 
among the countrys youth and intellectuals 
</TEXT>
