<TEXT>
governors at the education summit 
pressed the bush administration wednesday to free states and local 
districts from restrictions on federal school money and urged 
greater commitment to early childhood programs 
the two issues were among key themes emerging at the first 
working sessions of the twoday summit between president bush his 
cabinet and the nations governors 
of the first three sessions all of which were behind closed 
doors the most contentious was apparently on the topic the 
learning environment 
the moderator of the session federal drug policy coordinator 
william j bennett said in an often sarcastic summary to reporters 
that there was lots of talk about early childhood everyone 
agreed they like little children but he said that unless the 
nation did something about poor schools in later grades spending 
more money on early education programs would be a waste 
arkansas gov bill clinton in a summary of a second working 
session governance whos in charge said much of the 
discussion had to do with how to exchange red tape for results 
new mexico gov garrey carruthers a republican who cochaired 
that panel with democrat clinton told reporters that bush had 
spent 40 minutes in the session and had responded to governors 
pleas for more spending freedom with a challenge for more specifics 
on how states would demonstrate results in the absence of 
regulations 
carruthers said governors told the president let us do it our 
own way we will demonstrate that were doing it better 
a third session on how to revitalize the teaching profession 
centered on among other issues how to recruit more minorities 
but the discussion included a recognition that for a long time to 
come minority students will be taught mainly by white teachers 
said democratic washington gov booth gardner cochair of that 
group 
a twopage memo summarizing objectives for the summit by the 
national governors association outlined seven general national 
performance goals which members hoped would become more specific as 
the meetings progressed 
the memo a copy of which was given to the associated press on 
wednesday outlined points that governors were to make during 
closeddoor working sessions with bush 
those goals according to the document were that 
all children be ready for first grade by the time they reach 
the appropriate age 
student achievement levels rise to internationally 
competitive levels especially in math and science 
disparities in achievement between students of different races 
and economic backgrounds be dramatically reduced 
the number of students going to college or other higher 
education be greatly increased 
adult illiteracy be virtually eliminated 
schools have welltrained teachers and modern technology 
the memo proposed that once goals are set and steps taken to 
achieve them we should move to a report card issued every year 
on the efforts of students schools the states and the federal 
government 
the governors memo also suggested that the summit be used to 
push changes to give states more flexibility in using federal 
education dollars and to eliminate unnecessary regulation 
at an opening news conference the governors stressed national 
goals and played down the issue of federal money at the summit 
the federal funding question is not the major issue for this 
summit said clinton 
if we dont have national performance goals how are we going 
to move from the bottom to top in international exams in math and 
science how are we going to stop being the only advanced economy 
in the world that has no system for guaranteeing that all 
5yearolds are ready to start school he asked 
still on the issue of money the memo said governors would be 
calling on the federal government to keep commitments it has 
already made 
it suggested that governors urge bush to get each member of his 
cabinet to target federal resources to ten of the largest and most 
troubled districts and 50 to 100 poor rural districts to reduce 
racial and economic disparities in educational opportunities 
states for their part should agree to restructure the 
education system in each state work with the federal government 
to reduce losses in the student loan program and work toward 
drugfree schools the memo said 
