have a fire richards said 
nickey said firefighters cut out the planes bottom to free a 
man and a woman he said they were the only two still alive in the 
plane when he arrived 
a national transportation safety board investigation team was 
not expected to reach the airport until late wednesday richards 
said the plane possibly had a power failure or may have struck a 
power line 
a small brushfire was caused by a downed power line but it was 
not known if the plane hit the line as it crashed 
warren said the craft manufactured in 1975 had been owned and 
operated by the airline for two years he said the aircraft had no 
history of any kind of problems 
no cockpit voice recorder or flight data recorder was onboard 
because the devices arent required or even manufactured for that 
type of aircraft he said 
at the time of the crash winds were calm and visibility was not 
a problem although the sky was partly cloudy richards said 
gary mucho ntsb regional director said the plane normally is 
configured to carry 19 passengers and two crew members 
in 1986 a grand canyon airlines plane collided with a 
sightseeing helicopter inside the canyon killing 25 people in 
august 1983 10 people died when a sightseeing charter plan from 
las vegas smashed into a cliff near the canyons south rim a 
crashinvestigation report said the pilot encountered rough weather 
and could not climb out of the canyon 
in washington ntsb spokesman mike benson said the de havilland 
twin otter is a popular commuter plane that carries 20 passengers 
he said the model has been involved in 77 accidents since 1962 
including 25 that killed a total of 135 people over the same 
period the board lists 89 accidents at the grand canyon including 
28 that resulted in 105 fatalities 
