<TEXT>
middleaged person makes early withdrawals 
from ira and pays no penalty 
maybe that will never make it as a headline at the supermarket 
checkout stand but it is a feat that can be accomplished in real 
life quite possible to your financial benefit without breaking 
the law 
as millions of americans opened individual retirement accounts 
in recent years they were cautioned that they were tying up their 
money until the year in which they reached age 59 
any withdrawals from the account before then except in cases of 
death or disability are hit with a 10 percent penalty tax in 
addition to ordinary income tax 
however there is a littleknown poorly understood exception 
to this rule says the accounting firm of kpmg peat marwick 
people of any age can withdraw money from an ira provided they 
do so under a system that provides for roughly equal periodic 
payments based on their life expectancies 
to see how this works in practice consider this example 
provided by accountants deloitte haskins amp sells 
a 50yearold woman wants to start tapping a 250000 ira in 
which she has stashed a lumpsum payment from a former employer 
she consults the current tables published by the internal 
revenue service available at her library perhaps or her bank 
and determines that her statistical life expectancy is 331 years 
dividing 250000 by 331 she calculates that she can withdraw 
7553 this year subject to income taxes but no penalty 
when it comes time to make next years withdrawal she will 
recompute how much she is entitled to based on the remaining 
balance in her ira and the latest lifeexpectancy tables 
chances are the balance will be a bit more than 250000 then 
since she withdrew only about 3 percent of her money this year and 
can easily earn a higher interest rate on the remaining amount in 
the account 
if she wants to gain access to more money in the early years of 
her withdrawals she can figure what is coming to her using an 
annuity formula that also is based on life expectancy but adds 
an assumed future return on the capital she has invested 
with an assumed return of 9 percent she is entitled to a 
penaltyfree distribution of about 24000 this year 
once you commit yourself to either approach you must keep using 
it faithfully until you reach age 59 or more and have been taking 
the distributions for at least five years 
fail to meet this requirement and you are subject to something 
called a recapture tax that amounts to a reimposition of all 
the penalties you thought you had avoided 
now that you know how to do it is it time to rush out and start 
mining your ira gold not without some careful consideration 
financial advisers say 
as a general rule most individuals should leave their ira 
balances intact at least until retirement kpmg peat marwick says 
after all the point of most ira saving is to accumulate a nest 
egg specifically for the later years of your life when you may 
have less control over your financial circumstances than you did 
before 
furthermore the earlier you withdraw money from an ira the 
less time it has to enjoy the potent benefits of taxdeferred 
compounding 
but the early withdrawal strategy may have appeal in special 
situations for example when you feel your retirement can be 
secured from other sources and you see an opportunity to put your 
ira money to work elsewhere and it remains as an option for all 
ira savers should their needs change with time 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

