the house banking committee has voted to strip 
the treasury departments authority over lowinterest loans and 
loan guarantees to third world countries for buying hightech goods 
or construction services from us companies 
on a 2822 vote tuesday the committee effectively turned that 
authority over to the exportimport bank as part of a bill raising 
its tiedaid war chest by 200 million and imposing new 
environmental conditions on us approval of world bank and 
international monetary fund aid to underdeveloped countries 
us manufacturers have complained that the treasury in its 
effort to deter the use of such tiedaid packages by other other 
countries chiefly japan and france has been too tightfisted in 
approving loans and loan guarantees to finance their exports 
as a result the american companies claim they are losing out on 
2 billion to 4 billion a year in foreign contracts 
the bill also authorizes 400 million over the next five years 
for the multinational interamerican development bank to support 
loans in latin america and 150 million for a special imf account 
that subsidizes interest payments on loans owed by very poor 
countries especially in africa 
under the legislation which was approved by the committee on a 
voice vote the us representatives to the world bank and imf 
would be prohibited from approving loans for third world projects 
without an environmental assessment first 
the environmental measure was modified tuesday to allow for some 
exceptions after the treasury department threatened to recommend a 
veto of the bill unless it was given some discretion 
