<TEXT>
the united states should not fear a fortress 
europe when the 12nation european economic community forms a 
single trading market in 1993 a european community official said 
the united states and other european community trade partners 
will benefit considerably when the western european nations unify 
into one 4 trillion market with 320 million consumers said willy 
de clercq a member of the european parliament and chairman of its 
committee for external relations 
us business interests fear that local content regulations 
requiring many goods to be produced in european community nations 
and proposed technical standards for imports could result in 
barriers against us products and turn europe into a trading 
fortress 
these fears are unjustified de clercq said tuesday at a 
washingtonbrussels trade forum far from creating a fortress 
europe the creation of an internal market will create significant 
benefits for our trading partners 
he said the european community 1992 internal markets scheme 
which goes into effect jan 1 1993 will offer considerable 
opportunities to noncommunity interests selling to the european 
community 
those would include he said uniform standards and procedures 
increased investment opportunities and nondiscrimination against 
foreign companies with european community ties 
as for concerns that a selfabsorbed european community will 
become more protectionist de clercq said it would not be in our 
own interests to go down this road 
he noted that the european community relies much more on trade 
than the united states or japan the european community derives 13 
percent of its industrial and commercial goods from imports while 
it has captured 24 percent of the worlds export trade 
by comparison the united states has 8 percent of the world 
export market the japanese 16 percent he said 
tom duesterberg the assistant commerce secretary for 
international economic policy said the united states welcomed the 
european calls but still had major concerns over some provisions of 
european community 1992 
the united states still is worried about standards testing and 
certification procedures for us goods and by local content 
provisions on the auto and broadcasting industries duesterberg 
said 
