we can catch up 
republicans held their own strategy session where the 
democratic plan of substituting liberalized individual retirement 
accounts for a lower capitalgains tax was portrayed as an excuse 
to raise taxes iras would be financed by a tax increase on 
topincome americans 
its exactly the kind of tax increase democrats proposed 
in 1984 said rep newt gingrich of georgia the republican whip 
i think well find the extra five or six votes necessary to win 
the capitalgains cut is one of numerous divisive issues 
attached to a deficitreduction bill the house is considering 
the 2000page bill would reduce the deficit by 166 billion 
during the budget year that begins oct 1 enough to meet 
requirements of the grammrudman balancedbudget law and avoid 
automatic spending cuts in most federal programs 
because the legislation is so important and considered by some 
to be vetoproof it has become the vehicle to carry numerous 
amendments many having nothing to do with cutting the deficit 
but president bush said tuesday he would continue his fight for 
a lower capital gains tax even if it ties up the bill and triggers 
acrosstheboard cuts 
a president has to use the tools at his disposal to accomplish 
the ends for which he was elected bush said and i plan to do 
exactly that 
as the sparring on capital gains was taking on more urgency 
votes were expected today on lesser provisions one would block a 
decline in the 8 percent airline ticket tax and other aviation 
taxes and one would repeal a 1986 law requiring employers to prove 
their health insurance plans do not discriminate against lowerpaid 
workers 
the house is to decide thursday between a capital gains tax cut 
and a democratic alternative to expand taxdeductible individual 
retirement accounts 
votes are likely next week on proposals to repeal or modify 
catastrophic medical insurance for retirees and to boost benefits 
for child care for lowincome families 
the democratic leadership hoping to recover from a defeat in 
the house ways and means committee on the capital gains issue is 
instead proposing to expand iras 
bush contends a cut in taxes on capital gains profits from the 
sale of stock and other assets would spur saving and create jobs 
democrats say liberalized iras would serve the same purpose and 
provide more benefit to those with lower incomes 
at the white house on tuesday bush told business leaders he 
will fight for the tax cut even if that delays action on the 
deficit bill and triggers automatic spending reductions 
he said he would not accept the proposed ira liberalization 
which democrats want to finance by raising taxes on the wealthiest 
600000 couples and individuals bush also disputed democratic 
arguments that a capital gains cut is a windfall for the rich 
i think we ought to stand up to the understandable political 
rhetoric on the other side rhetoric that we heard all last year 
and that were now hearing once again he said 
rep barbara boxer dcalif a former stockbroker called the 
capital gains plan a quick fix for a quick profit for those who 
earn over 200000 a year 
as the house began what is expected to be a week and a half of 
debate on the spending bill few members bragged about the massive 
package 
some complained that many of the deficit reductions are phony 
simply shifting costs from one budget year to another others 
criticized the use of amendments that do nothing to cut the deficit 
some measures would outlaw obscene dialaporn phone 
services renew tax benefits for a variety of special interests 
raise the amount that social security recipients may earn without 
losing part of their pensions boost assistance for the poor and 
write into the law the fairness doctrine which would require 
broadcasters to air all sides of issues 
this is the melting pot act said rep steven schiff rnm 
