a group of seven cement manufacturers have 
complained to federal officials that mexican competitors unfairly 
are selling cement in the united states at cutrate prices 
the manufacturers committee made up of producers in texas 
arizona new mexico and florida said it filed petitions tuesday 
with the us international trade commission and the us commerce 
dept asking for duties on imports of gray portland cement large 
enough to eliminate any price differential 
dumping cement in us markets cannot be allowed to 
continue said clarence c comer chief executive of 
houstonbased southdown inc and head of the manufacturers group 
which claims the us price for the imported cement is about 
onehalf what mexicans are charged 
if we lose out to fair competition from mexico so be it 
comer said our investigation to date however convinces us that 
the mexicans success in us markets is due to dumping and not to 
any other factor 
since 1983 the group said seven cement plants have closed in 
arizona new mexico and texas with two more closing in florida 
last year mexican imports accounted for 14 percent of the market 
in the three border states and 22 percent of the florida market 
the group said 
mexican producers continue to build exportoriented capacity 
aimed at american markets comer said we dont want to see 
imports stopped or to deter fair competition but when dumping of 
cement hurts us companies and workers the time has come to 
