<TEXT>
opec ministers wednesday adjourned five days of 
sometimes heated talks by raising their production cap only a 
modest amount to try to strengthen crude prices in the coming 
months 
but the final accord still grossly understated the actual amount 
of oil the cartel is believed to be producing and at least three 
members said they would refuse to recognize the deal 
kuwait and the united arab emirates already producing beyond 
their assigned limits said they had no plans to restrain their 
pumping algeria declared the deal illegal 
opec president rilwanu lukman said the group would raise its 
output ceiling by a million barrels a day to 205 million barrels 
from 195 million for the final three months of the year various 
estimates put opecs actual production at closer to 225 million 
barrels a day 
the meeting of the 13nation organization of petroleum exporting 
countries ended in confusion after the ministers failed to resolve 
their deep divisions several countries reportedly had asked for a 
bigger share of the pie 
crude oil prices fluctuated during the talks as investors 
awaited a decision 
some analysts predicted the cartels decision would translate 
into even higher production and dampen prices 
fergus macleod analyst at barclays de zoete wedd in london 
said it means oil prices could weaken a bit from now on 
on the consumer side it may portend slightly lower prices 
said michael rothman analyst at merrill lynch capital markets in 
new york 
west texas intermediate the us benchmark crude was off about 
a dime at midday but closed 6 cents higher at 1959 a barrel on 
the new york mercantile exchange 
a basket of crudes monitored by opec had been trading about a 
dollar off the cartels target of 18 a 42gallon barrel 
lukman said the extra production would be divided 
proportionately among all 13 members each countrys quota or 
supply target would be raised by a certain amount 
lukman said the arrangement should mean slightly lower 
production well see a lot better prices he predicted 
indonesias oil minister ginandjar kartasasmita said he felt 
positive about the agreement 
the others are worried prices will go down he said i 
think at the minimum they will stay level 
kuwait and the united arab emirates have been ignoring their 
quotas to press their demands for bigger shares 
ali khalifa alsabah the kuwaiti oil minister said he made no 
commitments either legal or moral to anybody to hold down 
production 
the united arab emirates mana saeed otaiba said he did not 
intend to go along with the deal according to ginandjar 
sabah predicted demand would rise to 23 million barrels a day in 
the octoberdecember quarter 
hopefully he said that will keep prices at very near 
opecs reference price 
others however have estimated demand for opec oil at 22 
million barrels 
the decision to increase the ceiling was made after the 
ministers struggled for a day with a surprise iranian plan to solve 
the output demands of kuwait and the united arab emirates 
after failing to do so they settled on the stopgap measure 
immediately after the decision was announced the head of the 
algerian delegation who demanded anonymity said it is 
something that algeria doesnt associate itself with 
it is a decision that is illegal he said adding it was 
based on poor thinking 
the algerian minister sadek boussena returned to algiers on 
monday to attend a legislative meeting before his departure he 
had urged the participants to concentrate on getting prices up to 
the cartels 18 target 
the ministers were at odds throughout the meeting over how much 
they could raise any production ceiling without sending prices 
sliding 
opec secretarygeneral subroto said that if prices tumbled much 
the ministers would gather again opec has already planned a 
meeting for november to plan production strategy for 1990 
the ministers said they intended to take up the iranian plan 
again at that meeting 
iranian oil minister gholamreza aqazadeh said his proposal would 
raise the supply ceiling to 215 million barrels a day this he 
said would satisfy the demands of kuwait the united arab 
emirates gabon and ecuador for bigger slices of the production pie 
saudi arabia iran iraq and qatar would retain their current 
shares all others would lose some 
this would be the basis to solve the problems of opec 
hopefully for good aqazadeh said 
he said libya and the united arab emirates could not immediately 
go along with the plan libya has demanded the same share as kuwait 
each country is assigned an individual quota based on a formula 
of percentages for example saudi arabia the cartels no 1 
producer has nearly a 25 percent share of the total supply 
several opec members such as kuwait and the uae believe they 
are entitled to larger quotas based on production capacity 
opec members include algeria ecuador gabon indonesia iran 
iraq kuwait libya nigeria qatar saudi arabia the united arab 
emirates and venezuela 
