<TEXT>
sun co on wednesday announced it will begin 
testing a series of reformulated fuels and gasolines in hopes of 
lowering harmful emissions by 1993 
the new fuels will include a reformulated diesel a methanol mix 
and unleaded gasolines 
the first phase of the program will begin nov 1 when the 
company plans to market the new diesel fuel at selected 
philadelphiaarea service stations 
the fuel is designed to meet stricter environmental protection 
agency standards scheduled to take effect in 1993 the fuel will 
meet the proposed standard of 05 percent sulfur by weight the 
company said and will maintain a cetane rating of 45 cetane is 
the diesel equivalent of a gasolines octane rating 
in january the armellini trucking co will use the fuel on its 
floridatonew england runs testing will compare tailpipe 
emissions from the eight test trucks against emissions from four 
trucks not using the reformulated fuel the company said it expects 
to see reductions in sulfur emissions of up to 80 percent 
sun plans three tests for its methanol mix which will contain 
15 percent gasoline sun does not manufacture methanol but will 
blend the mixture known as m85 using methonal purchased from 
other producers 
m85 will be sold at selected sunoco service stations in detroit 
and washington dc starting in early 1990 but will be sold only 
to cars taking part in the experiment 
ford motor co is cooperating with the study by providing 
flexible fuel cars that can run on either gasoline or a mixture 
of methanol and gasoline up to 85 percent methonal sun said 
proponents of methanol claim substantial reductions in 
hydrocarbon emissions sun said but the company also plans to 
examine the emission of formaldehyde a gas that is an irritant 
the third phase of the program involves new unleaded gasolines 
sun currently markets gasoline under the sunoco brand in 28 states 
east of the rockies as well as under the atlantic brand in new york 
and pennsylvania 
several reformulated gasolines will be tested starting dec 1 
the reformulated gasolines will vary in composition but all will 
have reduced amounts of aromatics and olefins and increased amounts 
of oxygen compounds the company said 
the tests will involve a variety of post1975 cars that require 
unleaded gasoline the emissions will be compared with emissions 
levels from comparable cars running on existing sunoco economy and 
ultra automobile performence also will be evaluated 
the company expects to see reductions in carbon monoxide 
emissions of up to 10 percent 
the company declined to release information on how much the 
tests or the new fuel mixes will cost 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

