<TEXT>
president bush on wednesday urged western 
nations to increase their financial support for poland and a top 
polish official appealed for 15 billion to help his nation cope 
with a period of potentially explosive social conditions 
in his first address to the annual meetings of the international 
monetary fund and world bank bush praised the efforts of the 
solidarityled government to handle the economic crisis facing 
poland 
there may be no greater opportunity before us all today than 
the challenge of poland and more broadly eastern europe where 
countries are in the throes of dramatic political and economic 
change bush told the delegates from 152 nations 
the united states bush said will be in the forefront of aid 
efforts as eastern europes first noncommunistled government in 
four decades struggles with soaring inflation food shortages and a 
huge foreign debt 
he called on the imf and the world bank the top international 
lending agencies and western nations individually to boost their 
aid for poland 
in light of clearly growing needs the recent accession of a 
solidarityled government and our selfevident stake in its 
success we must do more bush said 
however he immediately told reporters hes not prepared to 
increase his 219 million us aid package saying any increase 
will be hinged on the success of the reform measures being drafted 
by the polish government 
the urgency of the situation was stressed by polish finance 
minister leszek balcerowicz who sought immediate assistance during 
a round of meetings with finance officials attending the imf and 
world bank meetings 
balcerowicz told reporters he wanted a 1 billion loan from 
western nations by early next year to provide critical reserves 
needed to stabilize exchange rates but poland also needs up to 
500 million in shortterm trade loans sooner to buy essential 
foreign goods such as fertilizer and medical drugs he said 
the reform process at least in its initial phase will 
proceed in extremely difficult and potentially explosive social 
conditions balcerowicz said pleading for western aid to ease 
the poles hardships 
he said he wasnt disappointed that bush didnt offer any 
specific figures on how much the united states might boost its aid 
proposal saying he expected the details to be forthcoming 
the administration is supporting a 119 million package of us 
economic aid to poland and another 100 million in food aid 
congressional democrats have termed the package woefully inadequate 
and called for more 
polish officials have sought 700 million a year over the next 
three years from the imf and there were indications that the imf 
assistance program could be approved as soon as november 
in his speech bush also stressed the need to keep pushing 
forward with his initiative to ease the 13 trillion burden of 
debt being carried by developing countries in latin america and 
elswhere 
the imf and the world bank have been supporting the effort by 
providing incentives to encourage commerical banks to forgive a 
portion of their loans to poor nations but banks have been 
reluctant to support the plan because it requires them to partially 
forgive old loans then make new loans 
bush made an even more blunt appeal to a group of commercial 
bankers at a white house reception tuesday night lobbying for the 
debtrelief plan put forward by treasury secretary nicholas brady 
british chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson told reporters 
wednesday that twisting bankers arms was a very foolish thing to 
do 
banks have to make their own decisions in light of their own 
assessment of their longterm interests he said 
later wednesday argentine president carlos menem announced that 
his country had reached agreement clearing the way for an imf loan 
to his nation the third largest debtor in the developing world 
with 60 billion owed 
an imf statement put the loan amount at 14 billion 
menem in a speech after a morning meeting with bush at the 
white house said argentina was facing the most dangerous 
economic crisis in our history because of hyperinflation a huge 
foreign debt and a stagnating economy 
the government must root out the structural causes of 
stagnation he said individual initiative and competitiveness 
within a market framework is the answer 
</TEXT>
