<TEXT>
a philadelphia brokerage accused of 
manipulating the price of a publicly traded stock has been fined 
50000 and suspended from the national association of securities 
dealers 
the nasd said wednesday the action was part of a crackdown on 
fraud and abusive sales practices in the pennystock market 
bailey martin amp appel inc was accused of violating the nasds 
antifraud provisions by artificially increasing the price of stock 
for northgate industries inc a shell corporation with no assets 
the brokerage neither admitted nor denied the allegations it 
settled the case by paying the fine and agreeing to the suspension 
two of the firms owners who also were suspended from the 
association denied any wrongdoing they said they had agreed to 
settle the case to prevent a long costly legal fight 
we feel theyve made an enormous mountain out of a molehill 
said donald bailey chairman of bma group ltd the holding company 
that owns bailey martin 
howard m appel a coowner of the firm said the sales involved 
only 30 clients and none had complained to the association which 
regulates overthecounter stocks 
the associations marketsurveillance committee filed a 
complaint in july stating that bailey martin had acquired 70 
percent of northgates stock at 20 cents per share shortly before 
it merged with starcom entertainment international inc a company 
with no operating history or revenues 
after the merger the brokerage increased the price of the stock 
to 3 per share an increase of 1400 percent by purchasing and 
selling shares at higher prices despite limited wholesale and 
retail demand for the stock the complaint said 
</TEXT>
